instructions:
## Set up Convex in Next.js

### 1. Install Convex
- Run:
  ```
  npm install convex
  ```
- No additional adapter packages needed — `convex` includes both the server SDK and React hooks.

### 2. Initialize Convex
- Run the Convex dev CLI to initialize the project:
  ```
  npx convex dev
  ```
- On first run, this will:
  1. Prompt you to log in (browser opens for OAuth).
  2. Create a new Convex project or link to an existing one.
  3. Create a `convex/` directory in your project.
  4. Add `NEXT_PUBLIC_CONVEX_URL` to your `.env.local`.
- Keep `npx convex dev` running alongside `npm run dev` during development — it deploys function changes in real-time.

### 3. Environment variables
- After `npx convex dev`, your `.env.local` will contain:
  ```
  NEXT_PUBLIC_CONVEX_URL=https://your-deployment.convex.cloud
  ```
- This is the only env var needed on the client side. It is safe to expose (no secret key).
- For production, add this env var to your hosting provider (e.g., Vercel).

### 4. Define your schema
- Create `convex/schema.ts` to define your tables:
  ```ts
  import { defineSchema, defineTable } from 'convex/server';
  import { v } from 'convex/values';

  export default defineSchema({
    tasks: defineTable({
      title: v.string(),
      completed: v.boolean(),
      userId: v.string(),
      createdAt: v.number(), // Unix timestamp
    }).index('by_user', ['userId']),

    users: defineTable({
      name: v.string(),
      email: v.string(),
      clerkId: v.optional(v.string()),
    }).index('by_clerk_id', ['clerkId']),
  });
  ```
- Convex validators: `v.string()`, `v.number()`, `v.boolean()`, `v.id('tableName')`, `v.array(...)`, `v.object({...})`, `v.optional(...)`.
- Indexes with `.index('name', ['field1', 'field2'])` enable efficient queries. Always add indexes for fields you filter or sort by.
- Schema changes auto-deploy when `npx convex dev` is running.

### 5. Write queries (read data)
- Create `convex/tasks.ts`:
  ```ts
  import { query, mutation } from './_generated/server';
  import { v } from 'convex/values';

  // Queries are read-only and run on the Convex server
  export const list = query({
    args: { userId: v.string() },
    handler: async (ctx, args) => {
      return await ctx.db
        .query('tasks')
        .withIndex('by_user', (q) => q.eq('userId', args.userId))
        .order('desc')
        .collect();
    },
  });

  export const getById = query({
    args: { taskId: v.id('tasks') },
    handler: async (ctx, args) => {
      return await ctx.db.get(args.taskId);
    },
  });
  ```
- Queries are reactive — when underlying data changes, all clients using this query auto-update.
- Use `.withIndex()` for filtered queries — it's much faster than `.filter()` on large datasets.
- `.collect()` returns all matching docs; `.first()` returns one; `.paginate()` for pagination.

### 6. Write mutations (write data)
- Add mutations to the same file or a new file:
  ```ts
  export const create = mutation({
    args: {
      title: v.string(),
      userId: v.string(),
    },
    handler: async (ctx, args) => {
      const taskId = await ctx.db.insert('tasks', {
        title: args.title,
        completed: false,
        userId: args.userId,
        createdAt: Date.now(),
      });
      return taskId;
    },
  });

  export const toggleComplete = mutation({
    args: { taskId: v.id('tasks') },
    handler: async (ctx, args) => {
      const task = await ctx.db.get(args.taskId);
      if (!task) throw new Error('Task not found');
      await ctx.db.patch(args.taskId, { completed: !task.completed });
    },
  });

  export const remove = mutation({
    args: { taskId: v.id('tasks') },
    handler: async (ctx, args) => {
      await ctx.db.delete(args.taskId);
    },
  });
  ```
- `ctx.db.insert()` → create a document, returns its `Id`.
- `ctx.db.patch()` → partial update (only specified fields).
- `ctx.db.replace()` → full replacement.
- `ctx.db.delete()` → delete by `Id`.

### 7. Write actions (call external APIs)
- Actions can call external HTTP APIs (queries and mutations cannot):
  ```ts
  import { action } from './_generated/server';
  import { v } from 'convex/values';

  export const sendEmailAction = action({
    args: { email: v.string(), name: v.string() },
    handler: async (ctx, args) => {
      const response = await fetch('https://api.resend.com/emails', {
        method: 'POST',
        headers: {
          Authorization: `Bearer ${process.env.RESEND_API_KEY}`,
          'Content-Type': 'application/json',
        },
        body: JSON.stringify({
          from: 'noreply@example.com',
          to: args.email,
          subject: 'Welcome!',
          html: `<p>Hello ${args.name}</p>`,
        }),
      });
      return { ok: response.ok };
    },
  });
  ```
- Store API keys as Convex environment variables (dashboard → Settings → Environment Variables), not in your Next.js `.env`.
- Actions can call mutations via `ctx.runMutation(api.tasks.create, { ... })`.

### 8. Set up the ConvexProvider in Next.js
- Create `src/components/providers/convex-provider.tsx`:
  ```tsx
  'use client';
  import { ConvexProvider, ConvexReactClient } from 'convex/react';
  import { ReactNode } from 'react';

  const convex = new ConvexReactClient(process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_CONVEX_URL!);

  export function ConvexClientProvider({ children }: { children: ReactNode }) {
    return <ConvexProvider client={convex}>{children}</ConvexProvider>;
  }
  ```
- Wrap your root layout:
  ```tsx
  // app/layout.tsx
  import { ConvexClientProvider } from '@/components/providers/convex-provider';

  export default function RootLayout({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
    return (
      <html lang="en">
        <body>
          <ConvexClientProvider>{children}</ConvexClientProvider>
        </body>
      </html>
    );
  }
  ```

### 9. Use queries and mutations in Client Components
- Import the auto-generated `api` object and Convex hooks:
  ```tsx
  'use client';
  import { useQuery, useMutation } from 'convex/react';
  import { api } from '@/convex/_generated/api';

  export function TaskList({ userId }: { userId: string }) {
    const tasks = useQuery(api.tasks.list, { userId });
    const createTask = useMutation(api.tasks.create);
    const toggleComplete = useMutation(api.tasks.toggleComplete);
    const removeTask = useMutation(api.tasks.remove);

    if (tasks === undefined) return <div>Loading...</div>;

    return (
      <div>
        <button onClick={() => createTask({ title: 'New Task', userId })}>Add Task</button>
        {tasks.map((task) => (
          <div key={task._id}>
            <input
              type="checkbox"
              checked={task.completed}
              onChange={() => toggleComplete({ taskId: task._id })}
            />
            {task.title}
            <button onClick={() => removeTask({ taskId: task._id })}>Delete</button>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    );
  }
  ```
- `useQuery` returns `undefined` while loading, then the data — always handle the loading state.
- `useMutation` returns a function you call with the mutation args.
- Data updates are **real-time**: any change from any client triggers an automatic re-render — no polling, no manual refetching.

### 10. Server-side data fetching (RSC / API Routes)
- Use `fetchQuery` for one-time server-side data fetching:
  ```ts
  import { fetchQuery } from 'convex/nextjs';
  import { api } from '@/convex/_generated/api';

  // In a Server Component or Route Handler
  const tasks = await fetchQuery(api.tasks.list, { userId: 'user_123' });
  ```
- This is a non-reactive one-shot fetch — use it for SSR/SSG, not for real-time features.
- `fetchMutation` and `fetchAction` work similarly for server-side writes.

### 11. Authentication with Clerk
- Install: `npm install @clerk/nextjs`.
- Add to `convex/auth.config.ts`:
  ```ts
  export default {
    providers: [
      {
        domain: 'https://your-clerk-domain.clerk.accounts.dev',
        applicationID: 'convex',
      },
    ],
  };
  ```
- In your provider, use `ConvexProviderWithClerk`:
  ```tsx
  'use client';
  import { ConvexProviderWithClerk } from 'convex/react-clerk';
  import { ConvexReactClient } from 'convex/react';
  import { useAuth } from '@clerk/nextjs';

  const convex = new ConvexReactClient(process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_CONVEX_URL!);

  export function ConvexClerkProvider({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
    return (
      <ConvexProviderWithClerk client={convex} useAuth={useAuth}>
        {children}
      </ConvexProviderWithClerk>
    );
  }
  ```
- Access the authenticated user in queries/mutations via `ctx.auth.getUserIdentity()`.

### Common errors & fixes
- **`NEXT_PUBLIC_CONVEX_URL is not defined`** — Run `npx convex dev` first to generate the env var, or manually add it from the Convex dashboard.
- **`Could not find public function for 'tasks:list'`** — The function isn't exported, has a typo, or `npx convex dev` isn't running. Check `convex/_generated/api.d.ts` to see available functions.
- **`useQuery returned undefined` forever** — `undefined` means loading. If it never resolves, check the Convex dev server is running and the URL is correct.
- **`Argument validation error`** — The args passed don't match the `v.*` validators in the function definition. Check types match exactly.
- **`Cannot use 'fetch' in a query or mutation`** — Queries and mutations run in a sandboxed environment without HTTP access. Move external API calls to an `action()`.
- **Schema validation error** — A document in the DB no longer matches the schema after a schema change. Use the Convex dashboard to inspect/fix data.
- **Stale `_generated` types** — Stop and restart `npx convex dev` to force regeneration of the `convex/_generated/` directory.

### What NOT to do
- Do NOT call Convex functions directly from Server Components using `useQuery` — hooks only work in Client Components. Use `fetchQuery` for server-side fetching.
- Do NOT access external APIs (HTTP fetch, Stripe, etc.) from queries or mutations — use actions for external calls.
- Do NOT store secrets in your Next.js `.env` for use inside Convex functions — set them via the Convex dashboard (Settings → Environment Variables) and access via `process.env` inside actions.
- Do NOT skip the schema — untyped documents lose the autocomplete, validation, and index benefits that make Convex safe.
- Do NOT use `.filter()` on large tables without an index — it performs a full table scan. Always add an index for fields you filter by.
- Do NOT create multiple `ConvexReactClient` instances — create one at the module level and reuse it.
- Do NOT confuse `mutation` with `action` — mutations are transactional and can't do HTTP; actions can do HTTP but aren't transactional. Use the right one for the job.
